<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-28T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-28T14:00:00-05:00" n="202" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d202">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/830: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-28T14:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            28, 1922—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 7:26
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>3. English translation of previous note of acceptance withdrawn and
                                new substitute note received. The number and date are the same, and
                                with the deletion of the phrase “adjusted by the Government <pb facs="0580" n="460" xml:id="pg_460"/> of the United States” the
                                phraseology of the two notes is exactly the same.</p>
                            <p>I believe that the Peruvian Government would be gratified if neither
                                note were published, and if possible I urge that their wishes be
                                respected.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>